  <h2>British Columbia Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    British Columbia has one of the most diverse growing climates in Canada. Coastal regions,
    interior valleys, mountain zones, and northern areas all behave differently. Your effective
    season depends far more on location and elevation than province-wide averages.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Coastal vs. Interior climates</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Coastal BC:</strong> Long frost-free windows, but moderate summer heat accumulation.</li>
    <li><strong>Interior Valleys:</strong> Hotter summers and strong GDD build — but earlier fall frost risk.</li>
    <li><strong>Mountain regions:</strong> Shorter seasons and rapid temperature swings.</li>
    <li><strong>Northern BC:</strong> Long daylight hours help growth, but frost windows are tight.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you garden at elevation, review how
    <a href="/guides/how-elevation-affects-growing-degree-days/">elevation affects growing degree days</a>
    before assuming your season matches a nearby town.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Mild winters don’t always mean strong summer heat</h3>
  <p>
    Coastal areas may avoid hard frost for much of the year, but cooler daytime highs can limit
    total growing degree day accumulation. Heat-loving crops like tomatoes and peppers often mature
    more slowly than gardeners expect.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    Days to maturity alone can be misleading in cooler climates —
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">
      here’s why maturity labels don’t always tell the full story
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Interior heat builds fast — then drops fast</h3>
  <p>
    In interior regions, July and early August can accumulate heat quickly. But once overnight
    lows begin trending downward, warm-season crops slow significantly. New long-maturity plantings
    after mid-summer are often risky without protection.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Microclimates are common</h3>
  <p>
    Even within the same community, gardens at slightly higher elevation or with good air drainage
    may avoid frost events that affect valley bottoms. Small differences in slope, exposure,
    and wind protection can shift real frost timing.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your yard runs warmer or colder than your zip code,
    <a href="/guides/why-your-backyard-may-be-warmer-or-colder-than-your-zip-code/">
      this guide explains why
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Check frost timing and remaining GDD for your nearest station.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity requirements to realistic seasonal heat.</li>
    <li>Add margin if you’re in a frost-prone valley or higher elevation.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    Use the tables above as your baseline, then confirm crop timing with the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>